  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Design Requirements**\n\nI\'ve been examining the design requirements, specifically focusing on the \"Lernwelt\" project. The target audience is German primary school children in Grades 1-4. The desired aesthetic is a \"Soft Tactile\" style with UI components resembling physical \"Learning Blocks.\" I\'m also considering friendly geometry with heavily rounded forms. I\'m starting to explore how motion, like gentle bounciness and squishiness, can enhance the micro-interactions.\n\n\n**Verifying Motion Import**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the \'motion\' import. My current goal is to ensure I\'m using the correct import path for animations, specifically focusing on `motion/react`. I\'ve checked the dependency versions and confirmed that in the installed version, importing from `motion/react` is the correct approach for React-specific bindings. I\'m now exploring the creation of a fleshed-out learning world, and its activities.\n\n\n**Mapping Learning Stations**\n\nI\'m developing a \'landkarte\' concept, a visual progress map for learning stations structured like an S-curve, presented as islands or floating blocks. I\'m focusing on activities for different grade levels. For instance, I\'m thinking of \"Buchstabensalat\" for Grade 1, \"Silben-H\303\274pfen\" for Grade 2, \"Wortarten-Sortierer\" for Grade 3, and \"Rechtschreib-Detektiv\" for Grade 4. I\'m imagining a mascot to guide these activities. I am torn between Lumi the dragon and Lumi the firefly!\n\n\n**Structuring the Framework**\n\nI\'m now focusing on establishing a clean and modular project structure. My immediate plan involves defining key data types in `/src/types.ts` to manage lesson states, user profiles, and progress. I\'m also preparing to build the UI components such as a mascot with expressive reactions in `/src/components/Mascot.tsx`. I am also planning the progress map for the learning blocks in `/src/components/LessonMap.tsx`. I\'m starting work on interactive exercises, and local, synthetic audio feedback using the Web Audio API!\n\n\n**Defining UI Components**\n\nI\'m now focusing on specific UI components. I\'ve started on `/src/components/StationWordTypes.tsx` and `/src/components/StationSpellingDetective.tsx`, corresponding to learning stations for sorting word types and spelling detection. I\'ve also begun a `/src/components/Certificate.tsx`, a gold medal certificate for task completion. I\'m investigating how to import the design fonts, and will use the Google Fonts import, as specified.\n\n\n**Implementing Design Tokens**\n\nI\'ve integrated the design token values within a Tailwind CSS theme extension, mapping each semantic color to corresponding hex values. I am updating font imports, and confirmed the font is \"Quicksand\" from the Google fonts import. I am confident this ensures design consistency and maintainability across the UI.\n\n\n**Refining Font Definitions**\n\nI\'m now refining font definitions, planning how to use Tailwind classes for typography. I\'ve decided to map `font-sans` to Plus Jakarta Sans for headings and `font-body` to Quicksand for body text and buttons. I am reading `index.css` to plan the integration of Google Fonts, design variables, and custom helper classes for that \"Soft Tactile\" aesthetic. I am writing some initial Tailwind shadow and border classes.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the `/src/types.ts` file to model the stations, lessons, profile settings, and exercises in our application. This ensures strict type safety."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 13
      nanos: 177212151
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
